com.travelbank.knit

Class InternalModel

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.travelbank.knit.InternalModel
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    MemoryEntity, ModelInterface
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    ModelManager

    public abstract class InternalModel
extends java.lang.Object
implements ModelInterface
    This class is the master class of KnitModel that is exposed to the user. Knit's annotation processor creates these InternalModels that initialize and contain the actual KnitModel. All KnitModels annotated with a Model will have an internal counterpart that manages them. The master class created by the processor will have a name "ClassName" + "_Model". Actual KnitModel instance will be wrapped around an Exposer class that will expose all of it's public and package-private methods to the InternalModel . Instance of these, once initialized, are registered to the ModelManager.
    See Also:
    Model, KnitModel

      • requestImmediately

        public abstract <T> KnitResponse<T> requestImmediately(java.lang.String data,
                                                       java.lang.Object... params)
        Method call that handles how data requests to the model from the KnitPresenter and other models are done. No async support. Runs on the thread it is called on via a ImmediateScheduler. Use these in umbrella models.
        Type Parameters:
        T - type of the response body.
        Parameters:
        data - data the tag of the data that is requested. ValueGenerator for it must be annotated with a Generates with the value of this parameter.
        params - Extra parameters being passed to the ValueGenerator
        Returns:
        KnitResponse being returned from the associated ValueGenerator.

      • input

        public abstract void input(java.lang.String data,
                           java.lang.Object... params)
        Used when simply inputting/storing data. Make sure your task doesn't need to return a response. No async support. If you need to return a response and want your task to run on a SchedulerInterface, use this#request(String, KnitSchedulers, KnitSchedulers, EntityInstance, Object...) and return true or false depending on how input task went.
        Parameters:
        data - data the tag of the data that is being input. Inputter1 for it must be annotated with a Inputs with the value of this parameter.
        params - Extra parameters being passed to the Inputter1.
